          <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" vspace="0" hspace="0">
  <tr><td width="2" height="15"><img src="/lotr/gfx/center_column/1.gif" width="2" height="25"></td>
    <td width="700" background="/lotr/gfx/cloud/redcc.gif" height="15" valign="bottom"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
        <tr><td><font face="Tolk, Times, serif" class="h1font"><font color="#C46161"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font face="Tolk, Times, serif" class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/treports/treports.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td width="2"></td><td valign="top"> 
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5"><tr><td><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"><font face="Tolk, Times, serif" class="h1font"> Niles, Illinois 19 Jan 2002<br></font><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8874'>Adam "ramolnar" Molnar</A></font><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8874&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font face="Papy, Times, serif" class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"> Tournament Report<br>
Pastimes, Niles, Illinois<br>
19 January 2002<br>
12 participants<br>
<br>
Pretourney:  Having played Rangers without Versatility and Isengard for a long time now, I decide it&#39;s time for a change.  I build a Gandalf/Sauron deck, but Sauron relies too heavily on getting the conditions early for my taste, plus Sleep Caradhras hurts a lot.  Playtest partner Jeremy just trounced it with his Gandalf deck a couple times.  So I gave in and build Gandalf/Nazgul along the lines of Jeremy&#39;s that won last tournament, though I run rare Legolas for a little more Moria protection.  Unfortunately, I built the deck about 3 cards wrong, and it turned a great archetype into a merely good one.  Here&#39;s the decklist, after I traded for the third Gimli on site; guess what cards are wrong:<br>
<br>
Frodo, Son of Drogo<br>
The One Ring, Isildur&#39;s Bane<br>
Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk<br>
<br>
3 Aragorn, Ranger of the North<br>
2 Legolas Greenleaf<br>
3 Gimli, Son of Gloin<br>
1 Boromir, Lord of Gondor<br>
2 Barliman Butterbur<br>
1 Albert Dreary<br>
2 Glamdring<br>
2 Sting<br>
2 Ranger&#39;s Sword<br>
1 Gimli&#39;s Battle Axe<br>
1 Gimli&#39;s Helm<br>
2 Sleep, Caradhras<br>
4 Servant of the Secret Fire<br>
2 Intimidate<br>
1 Armor<br>
1 Athelas<br>
1 A Ranger&#39;s Versatility<br>
<br>
3 Witchking<br>
2 Ulaire Attea<br>
2 Ulaire Toldea<br>
3 Ulaire Cantea<br>
3 Ulaire Nelya<br>
2 Ulaire Enquea<br>
2 Ulaire Lemenya<br>
2 Relentless Charge<br>
2 All Blades Perish<br>
3 Black Breath<br>
3 Blade Tip<br>
1 The Pale Blade<br>
3 Nazgul Sword<br>
1 Morgul Blade<br>
<br>
The Prancing Pony<br>
Bree Streets<br>
Ford of Bruinen<br>
Moria Lake<br>
Bridge<br>
Galadriel&#39;s Glade<br>
Anduin Wilderland<br>
Brown Lands<br>
Summit of Amon Hen<br>
<br>
This deck does wonders in the late game, but Gandalf decks are weak early, and I didn&#39;t take that enough into account.  The Ranger&#39;s Versatility combo relies on Legolas and Versatility, but that sets up too late.  Plus lots of people in Chicago run the Pony.  So, I&#39;d drop the Versatility, and change the third Aragorn to an Arwen, so I can have another chance of pulling an early companion.  Gandalf decks beat Nazgul by having enough companions early to not get Gandalf (and to a lesser extent Aragorn) in trouble before Gandalf becomes 11+ and Aragorn 10, and the Servants get into hand.  The Athelas is nonstandard, but it&#39;s there to pull a Black Breath off of Gandalf; it&#39;s not a bad card, but others might want to pitch it or substitute another companion.  On the shadow side, a Nazgul Sword should become a Black Breath, because getting that at the Ford is just vicious.  I&#39;d pull one Lemenya for space, and run 16 minions and 15 support cards.  That&#39;s pushing it, though, because you really need to have one Nazgul to drop each move.  I only didn&#39;t have the Ulaire in one game, and that was due to external circumstances (see below).<br>
<br>
Metagame<br>
The tourney ran really well; trading from noon to 12:25, then we completed five rounds and announced winners by 5 PM.  Thanks to Glenn for the smoothness.  Unlike Games Plus, there weren&#39;t a lot of dabblers or new people here (Pastimes is a little more serious site). Six people ran Nazgul, including both Jeremy and I; the other Shadow cultures were scattered.  On the fellowship side, five Versatility and three Gandalf were the order of the day.<br>
I&#39;ve changed my mind about viable Shadow a bit, as Sauron relies a bit too much on conditions for my taste.  Nazgul and Isengard are the tops around here, opposing the everpresent Versatility and less common Gandalf decks.  My playtest group likes Gandalf, because we hate conditions.  Sauron must have conditions, and Moria needs They are Coming and Goblin Swarms and Goblin Armory more than first suspected.  However, Gandalf decks require a lot of rares (I have 20 in my Fellowship), which makes it a rich-players deck; same with Nazgul.  Versatility requires less rares, and Isengard can run reasonably well with just a couple Lurtz and Spies of Saurman, so that build should be more common.<br>
Isengard and Sauron are stronger against Rangers, thanks to Spies of Saurman and no general condition removal, while Nazgul is much better against Gandalf with the quicker start.  Thus, the best deck depends a lot on the number of Gandalf decks around.  If everyone&#39;s going Versatility, run Isengard or Sauron direct damage; if there are even a few good Gandalf decks around, you need to go Nazgul.  I&#39;d put Sauron Enduring Evil in a speciality category, outstanding if people bid high but pretty poor if people bid intelligently.  Finally, Moria certainly has the potential for the victory out of nowhere, but there are a lot of ways to defeat it, and it&#39;s not as rare-free as some might think (between Cave Troll, Goblin Swarms, and Goblin Armory).<br>
On the fellowship side, Versatility is starting to become more common in Chicagoland, because it&#39;s a very good deck.  As shown above, well built and played Gandalf decks can do great things as well.  One needs to watch the matchup, though; Gandalf decks start slowly, and shouldn&#39;t be paired with Sauron or slow Isengard development.  Rangers start more quickly, and tend to play cards as they get them, so they can match with the slower Shadow halves.  Yes, I know I love Rangers twilight denial (No Strangers and pumpers instead of Versatility), but I seem to be in the minority there.  Other fellowships, like Hobbits, Hobbits and Men, and Dwarves, don&#39;t have the staying power at this point, at least on the Midway.<br>
<br>
Tournament report<br>
Playing Nazgul doesn&#39;t involve a lot of strategic decisions for me, it seems; drop one or two, throw on a sword, and Black Breath/Blade Tip whoever you can.  So there&#39;s not as much detail here as in some of my other reports, I&#39;m sorry.  There are more decisions for the Gandalf half, but against Nazgul it&#39;s basically just &quot;win what you can, Sleep when you must, survive if they let you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Round 1: Bobby, Versatility / Nazgul<br>
Bobby is Jeremy&#39;s brother, and knows my deck from playtesting; he also knows his Nazgul are far inferior to mine.  I get the Legolas, Boromir, and Pony start, and at that point we know the game&#39;s pretty much over.  There&#39;s not much to say here, as my Nazgul continue to slowly hurt him from the Ford on through Moria, and he can&#39;t get a kill on anyone.  Finally, at the Bridge, I cut him down to just Frodo and one other exhausted companion, and at site 6, that&#39;s the end.  There&#39;s just not much to say about Nazgul slicing and dicing.<br>
Full win (1-0, 3 pts)<br>
<br>
Round 2: Luke, Elf Ally / Nazgul<br>
Luke&#39;s running an interesting fellowship, with Boromir and Aragorn his only companions, lots of man support cards, and a few Elf allies, but no Legolas or Arwen.  I win the 1-1 roll, start the Pony, then explain that he can start Boromir instead of Aragorn as he was going to do.  I get Boromir on the start again, and with the Pony, things are OK.  Luke has only four rare Nazgul, and so he doesn&#39;t slow me down much.  On the other hand, fierce Nazgul do nasty things to people who rely on pump cards.  Luke does pretty well, but makes a mistake at site 4.  I&#39;ve got five pretty healthy companions, am ahead, and just looked at his hand with Sting and know he has a Seen and Unseen.  He draws and plays Rumil or somebody, then uses Athelas to remove conditions except a Blade Tip on once-wounded Boromir.  Aragorn has two wounds, I think.  He gets set to move, and I ask &quot;No Seen and Unseen?&quot; He says no, and moves.  Two Nazgul come down at the Bridge; he manages to win one skirmish, but Aragorn dies and Boromir takes his second wound.  So he gets killed shortly thereafter.  It wouldn&#39;t have mattered much, really, but Boromir might have stayed alive somewhat longer.<br>
Full Win (2-0, 6 pts)<br>
<br>
Round 3: Beau, Versatility / Moria<br>
Beau&#39;s fellowship is more archery based than others, with more allies.  I win the random roll on 1-1 and go first (yes, I know this seems crazy), rolling through to Rivendell even though I only have Gandalf and Aragorn.  He stops at 2.  I cautiously move to 4, he takes some pain at 3.  I can move forward pretty well, even at the Bridge, because he&#39;s drawing few minions for a Moria deck. BUT he gets Galadriel and the Mirror out at the Sanctuary.  Beau notes, &quot;So many people complained about this that I thought it must be good.&quot;  Ladies and gentlemen, the combo is still vicious, so please quit whining about how it no longer works.  Thank you.  Beau pulls two minions out at site 3, but thankfully I have one more so he stops at 4.  I move to 6, but he gets to pull another minion out via Galadriel and Celeborn trickery; combined with Elf allies, he gets to Lorien with 4 companions left.  I get Legolas out at the sanctuary, and everybody&#39;s healed; I use Frodo to check his hand, and he has a Cave Troll, and Host of Thousands.  So I move, he Hosts a Keyward, uses Relics of Moria to get a Hammer, and I see Keyward and 18/damage +2 Troll.  I take my licks on Gandalf and Sworded Aragorn, dealing two to the Keyward without archery support.  I know he has no other minions in hand, and is drawing two cards.  What would you do?<br>
<br>
Yes, I do perhaps the most inconceivable thing in the world, press on with a Cave Troll with Hammer on the table.  Beau laughs... but only plays one more minion.  So I can use Legolas to off the Keyward, Gandalf swats down some puny thing, and I pitch Legolas and Aragorn to the troll.  But I&#39;m at site 8, and I&#39;ve cleared enough cards to find a Gimli.  Combined with the Battle Axe that avoids the Mirror (though he does pull a Servant), and his lack of minions at site 9, I win.  His next four cards in his deck were minions, though.<br>
Full Win (3-0, 9 pts)<br>
<br>
Round 4: Eric, Versatility / Nazgul<br>
Eric&#39;s 2-1, having defeated Jeremy at site 9 and losing only a timed loss.  It&#39;s his first tourney, he&#39;s young, and he&#39;s running 70 cards, but it&#39;s a very good build, which I saw afterwards - 4 Witch Kings and all the Ranger trickery.  He bids high and goes first, I get no extra companions.  He starts uncommon Legolas because he knows my deck, gets Aragorn and the Bow out first turn, and guns down my Witch King, exhausting Aragorn.  I have a Relentless Charge in hand, so if he doesn&#39;t have the Versatility, I get rid of Aragorn and probably win.  Well, my luck&#39;s run out, and that doesn&#39;t happen.  Meanwhile, I can&#39;t find any other companions.  At the Bridge, I also have Legolas, but down comes the Witch King, and Ostea with sword.  The last twilight available for the sword kills me, because exhausted Gandalf with Glamdring can&#39;t kill Ostea without my nonexistant Servant, so I lose everybody but Frodo (Aragorn and Legolas, then Legolas and Gandalf).  Without Sting, I have no answer to the Lemenya for 4 twilight at the next site.  So I lose to Lemenya.  For his first tourney, Eric played well against me, and pulling the Versatility at the right time did the deed.<br>
Full Loss (3-1, 10 pts)<br>
<br>
Round 5: Jeremy, Gandalf / Nazgul<br>
Well, it was time; I have great tiebreakers, so if I win I&#39;ll be first, while if Jeremy wins it&#39;ll be close between him and Eric.  When we tested this, we found that going first in the mirror gave an advantage, interestingly enough.  I know he has only 2 Nazgul Swords, so I take a risk (I would say a big risk, but very little really compares to moving with a Troll on the table), win the bid 2-1, and go first.  I get an Aragorn, but no other companions in the draw.  He Ponies and gets two other companions after I make one move.  The game is basically over at this point unless I get companions quickly, and I don&#39;t.  I&#39;d like to say I made a mistake, or didn&#39;t cycle cards ruthlessly enough, but neither he nor I could see a different play afterwards.  I do manage to not let him double jump, though my companions get eaten alive one by one, till I&#39;m down to just Black Breathed exhausted Gandalf and Frodo at Lorien.  So I have to move, he gets Attea plus a Morgul Blade plus one twilight.  Unfortunately, Servant costs one, so I can&#39;t push Attea at Frodo and Servant once.  Game over.<br>
Full Loss (3-2, 11 pts)<br>
<br>
Eric wins on tiebreakers, with Jeremy second, and Jesse (from last week, still playing Versatility and Isengard) finishes third at 4-1, due to his timed win over Eric.  I&#39;m fourth, grumble.  Here, I want to make a comment about Opposition scores.  While the current procedure isn&#39;t a bad idea, it doesn&#39;t take into account the possibility of someone dropping - then they receive no points for the later rounds, and it really hurts someone who played them early.  I&#39;d suggest an Opposition per round adjustment.  I&#39;d also really like to see head-to-head, either as the first or at least the second tiebreak.  Then again, I have to win enough to get there....<br>
Good luck in all your journeys. <br></font></blockquote><BR><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=3290&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font face="  Times, Times New Roman, serif" class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr></table>
